    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The balls used in a golf tournament have diameter of <m>4.2 \text{cm}</m> 
                and <m>4.4 \,\text{cm}</m>. What is the difference in the surface area between the largest 
                and smallest golf ball?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The diameter of the smallest ball is <m>4.2\,\text{cm}</m>, so its radius is <m>r_1 = \frac{4.2}{2} = 2.1\,\text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The diameter of the largest ball is <m>4.4\,\text{cm}</m>, so its radius is <m>r_2 = \frac{4.4}{2} = 2.2\,\text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The formula for the surface area of a sphere is:
                <me>\text{SA} = 4\pi r^2</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                For the smallest ball:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{SA}_1 = \amp 4 \times \pi \times (2.1)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 4 \times \pi \times 4.41</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 17.64\pi</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                For the largest ball:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{SA}_2 = \amp 4 \times \pi \times (2.2)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 4 \times \pi \times 4.84</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 19.36\pi</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The difference in surface area is:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Difference} = \amp 19.36\pi - 17.64\pi</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 1.72\pi</mrow>
                </md>

                If <m>\pi = 3.142</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Difference} = \amp 1.72 \times 3.142</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 5.40224\,\text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the difference in surface area between the largest and smallest golf ball is <m>{\color{blue}5.40\,\text{cm}^2}</m> .
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

